   Suppose `n > 1` and `n ∣ 2ⁿ + 1`. Let `p` be the smallest prime divisor of `n`.  
   Then `p ∣ 2ⁿ + 1`, so `2ⁿ ≡ -1 (mod p)`.  
   Squaring gives `2^{2n} ≡ 1 (mod p)`.  
   The multiplicative order of `2` modulo `p`, denoted `d`, divides `2n`.  
   But also, by Fermat’s Little Theorem, `2^{p-1} ≡ 1 (mod p)`, so `d ∣ p - 1`.  
   Since `p` is the smallest prime dividing `n`, `gcd(n, p - 1) = 1` (because all prime factors of `p - 1` are smaller than `p`).  
